,"1340":"1340","1384":"1384","1295":"1295","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","Trethewyn, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Killigrew, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1295–":"1295–Deceased","1295–Male":"1295–Deceased","1298–1340":"1298–1340","1343–1384":"1343–1384","1270–Male":"1270–Deceased","1290–1365":"1290–1365","1314":"1314","1343":"1343","1365":"1365","1298":"1298","1340":"1340","1384":"1384","1295":"1295","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","Trethewyn, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Killigrew, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Killigrew","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Cornish: locative name from Killigrew in Saint Erme (Cornwall)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>George</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"George","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]},{"name":"or","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally the name of the god of thunder in Norse mythology, Thor (Old Norse <i>Þórr</i>). It was not used as a personal name during the Middle Ages. The modern name is either a late 18th-century revival of the god's name or else a vernacular development of   Tord ."],"variants":[{"name":"Thor","meanings":["Originally the name of the god of thunder in Norse mythology, Thor (Old Norse <i>Þórr</i>). It was not used as a personal name during the Middle Ages. The modern name is either a late 18th-century revival of the god's name or else a vernacular development of   Tord ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Thomas or John Killigrew II was born in 1295, his father, Sir Otho Killigrew, was 25 and his mother, Joan Canterbury, was 5. He married Lady Mary Poltesmore in 1340, in Cornwall, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1295–":"1295–Surnud","1295–Male":"1295–Surnud","1298–1340":"1298–1340","1343–1384":"1343–1384","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1290–1365":"1290–1365","1314":"1